 today while it questions the make-up of the fantasies and the capitalistic conditions of the play involved. Arguing that part of the appeal of such dream worlds is the polymorphous perversity with which they scramble identity and character, the author traces the postindustrial milieux from which such fantasies have arisen in postwar Japan and been popularly received in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnimated filmszJapan. 0aConsumer goodszJapan. 0aGameszJapan. 0aPhilosophy, Japanese. 0aToy industryzJapan. 0aToyszJapanxMarketing. 0aToyszJapan. 0aVideo gameszJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aanimation.  aanime.  acanada.  acapitalism.  acomic books.  acultural goods.  acultural studies.  aglobal consumption.  aglobal culture.  aglobal imagination.  aglobal marketplace.  aglobalization.  ahong kong.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese toys.  akaraoke.  amade in japan.  amanga.  amartial arts.  amedia studies.  amillennials.  anonfiction.  apopular toys.  apostindustrial.  apostwar japan.  asocial science.  asushi.  atechnoware.  atoy industry.  aunited states.  avideo games.  ayouth products.1 aCross, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022148240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093899140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938991423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938991/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Pack